#Text=Check Internet Speed
#Text=This wikiHow teaches you how to see the upload speed and download speed of your Internet connection , as well as the speed of the connection between your computer and your router .
#Text=Knowing your Internet speed can help you figure out what you can do with your internet connection .
#Text=Steps
#Text=Running an Internet Speed Test
#Text=Go to the Google Speed Test page .
#Text=Open a Google search page by going to https://www.google.com in a web browser or open the Google app on your device and type into the search field .
#Text=This will bring up an " Internet speed test " window at the top of the Google search results .

column1: #Text=Wait for the speed test to complete .
#Text=Google will measure your Internet connection 's upload speed , download speed , and latency .
#Text=Review the test results .
#Text=In addition to telling you whether your Internet qualifies as " fast " or " slow " , Google measures three aspects of your Internet 's speed :
#Text=Mbps download
#Text=- The number of megabits per second your connection is allowing you to download .
#Text=Mbps upload
#Text=- The number of megabits per second your connection is uploading .
#Text=Latency
#Text=-
#Text=The number of milliseconds it takes for your Internet connection to respond to a command ( e. g. , a search query or a page loading ) .
#Text=Checking Internet Speed on Windows
#Text=Make sure your computer is connected to your router .
#Text=To check your Internet speed from your computer 's settings , you must connect your computer to your router via Ethernet cable .
#Text=Open Start .
#Text=This icon is in the bottom-left corner of the screen .
#Text=Click .
#Text=It 's in the bottom-left corner of the Start window .
#Text=Click Network & Internet .
#Text=It 's in the top row of settings on the Settings page .
#Text=Click .
#Text=This tab is on the left side of the window .
#Text=Doing so will open your Ethernet settings .
#Text=Click .
#Text=It 's in the upper-right side of the window .
#Text=Double-click the Ethernet connection .
#Text=You 'll see this monitor-shaped icon at the top of the Network Connections window .
#Text=Review the " Speed " value .

column1: #Text=It 's near the bottom of the " Connections " section of information on the Ethernet Status window .
#Text=The number here ( e. g. , " 90.0 Mbps " ) represents the speed of the connection between your computer and the router .
#Text=Checking Internet Speed on Mac
#Text=Make sure your computer is connected to your router .
#Text=To check your Internet speed from your computer 's settings , you must connect your computer to your router via Ethernet cable .
#Text=Open Spotlight .
#Text=It 's in the top-right corner of your Mac 's screen .
#Text=Type " network utility " into Spotlight , then press .
#Text=Doing so will open the Network Utility app .
#Text=Click the tab .
#Text=It 's on the far-left side of the top of the Network Utility window .
#Text=Select your Ethernet connection .
#Text=Click the box below the " Select a network interface for information " heading , then click your Ethernet connection 's name .
#Text=Look at the number next to " Link Speed " .
#Text=You 'll see something like " 100 Mbit/s " here , which would mean the speed of the connection between your computer and your router is 100 megabits of data per second .
#Text=Troubleshooting
#Text=Switch to a wired connection .
#Text=If your wireless connection is experiencing significant lag , then you may need to connect to a wired connection ( usually through Ethernet ) in order to boost your Internet performance speed .
#Text=Restart your Wi-Fi access point .
#Text=Sometimes , routers or other devices that can access wi-fi may need to be restarted in order to fix any performance issues caused by a glitch or broken connection .
#Text=Connect to another network .
#Text=In order to check if the problem is a network or just your device , connect to another network you have access to and check that network 's Internet speed .
#Text=Run a malware scan on your device .
#Text=In some instances , a slow Internet speed could mean your device is being slowed down by malware in its system .
#Text=To remedy this , install an antivirus program with a malware scanner included in it .
#Text=Tips
#Text=Your Internet 's true connection speed is often much lower than your router 's maximum speed .
#Text=Using Ethernet allows you to take advantage of your router 's speed .
#Text=Benchmarks for common features include : 5 Megabits per second for HD streaming and 90 kilobits per second for VOiP calling
#Text=Warnings
#Text=Your Internet speed will never exceed either your router 's maximum speed or your Internet plan 's maximum speed -- whichever speed is lower .
#Text=Quick Summary
